    "active_paradigms": [
      {
        "idea": "Concentration-scaled half-time sigmoid: y = c4 * ((1 + tanh(c0 * x1^c1 * (x0 - c2 * x1^c3))) / 2)^c5 + c6",
        "description": "Replace the current growth term with an explicit concentration-dependent half-time. In secondary nucleation kinetics (Knowles 2009, Cohen 2013), the half-time scales as t_half ~ [M]^(-gamma) where gamma depends on the nucleation mechanism. This means the inflection point of the sigmoid should shift with concentration as c2*x1^(-c3), not just subtract a constant. The full growth term becomes c0*x1^c1*(x0 - c2*x1^c3), which correctly captures how both the rate AND the half-time scale with concentration. Add Richards exponent c5 for asymmetry. This is 7 constants but complexity ~26, parsimony factor ~0.967 vs current 0.9725, requiring meaningful NMSE improvement to justify.",
        "what_to_optimize": "Validation NMSE on concentration-varying datasets where half-time shifts with x1",
        "cautions": "x1^c3 can be unstable if x1=0 or c3 has wrong sign; ensure x1>0 always (concentration is positive). Initial values: c0=5, c1=0.5, c2=0.5, c3=-0.5, c4=1, c5=2, c6=0. Complexity increases slightly.",
        "approach_type": "sympy.expression.factored_halftime"
      },
      {
        "idea": "Logistic growth with additive baseline: y = c3 / (1 + exp(-c0 * (x0 - c1 * x1^c2))) + c4",
        "description": "Use a standard logistic (special case of Richards with exponent=1) but with explicit concentration-dependent half-time c1*x1^c2. This is simpler than the current model (5 constants, complexity ~18) and may be more robust across datasets. The logistic avoids the Richards exponent instability on datasets with limited data. The half-time c1*x1^c2 captures the power-law scaling from secondary nucleation. This reduces complexity from 22 to ~18, improving parsimony factor from 0.9725 to ~0.9775, and may be more numerically stable for small datasets. The tradeoff is losing the Richards asymmetry parameter.",
        "what_to_optimize": "Parsimony penalty improvement + robustness on small datasets with few curves",
        "cautions": "exp() can overflow for large arguments; ensure growth term stays bounded. Use soft_l1 loss (already used by evaluator). Initial values: c0=5, c1=0.5, c2=0.5, c3=1, c4=0.",
        "approach_type": "sympy.expression.logistic_conc_halftime"
      },
      {
        "idea": "Two-phase model: baseline + sigmoid scaled by concentration power: y = c5 * x1^c4 * ((1 + tanh(c0*(x0 - c1))) / 2)^c2 + c3",
        "description": "Separate the concentration scaling from the temporal sigmoid. In many aggregation experiments, the plateau amplitude scales with monomer concentration as [M]^alpha (mass conservation). The half-time in this form is a constant c1 (fitted per dataset), and the amplitude scales as c5*x1^c4. This is structurally different from the current model which couples x0 and x1 multiplicatively. For datasets where x1 modulates amplitude more than kinetics, this form may fit better. Keep Richards exponent c2 for asymmetry. This has 6 constants and complexity ~24, similar parsimony to current but different coupling structure.",
        "what_to_optimize": "Datasets where concentration affects plateau amplitude more than half-time (e.g., seeded experiments)",
        "cautions": "x1^c4 with negative c4 can diverge; x1 is always positive (concentration) so this is safe. The half-time c1 is now concentration-independent which may hurt datasets with strong concentration-dependent kinetics. Initial values: c0=5, c1=0.5, c2=2, c3=0, c4=1, c5=1.",
        "approach_type": "sympy.expression.amplitude_scaled_sigmoid"
      }
    ],
